<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> My Opinion: The Top RotEL Cards<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.56)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8062'>Michael "Big Yoda" Walklate</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8062&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 17, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I am sure that I will regret doing this article. I will probably get 17 one star ratings from people that disagree with some card in my top 10. I was inspired to do this by the article &quot;The 10 best cards of Realms&quot; by Wouter &quot;Venator&quot; Neyt. I strongly disagree with many of his choices but it really set me thinking. <br>
<br>
What makes a truly great card? Well to be a truly great card I would say that it has to be the sort of card that makes people think about how they are going to handle it in a game when they design their decks. This includes such existing cards as ARV, Blade Tip, They Are Coming (and Goblin Armories/Goblin Swarms), Legolas Greenleaf (and Aragorn&#39;s Bow), The Balrog, Under the Watchful Eye (and Orc Bowmen), PaTHS, Hobbit Stealth, The Witch King and Lurtz. <br>
<br>
Having played in the pre-release tournament on the weekend I noticed several cards already that were very strong. Obviously none of these cards have been tested in open tournaments yet and hindsight may well prove me wrong. <br>
<br>
First off I must say that I think there are lost more good cards in this set than in MoM. Yes there were some good cards in MoM such as Balrog, Flaming Brand, Mithril Coat, <br>
Gloin, Gandalf&#39;s Staff, Secret Sentinels, Uruk Scout, Goblin Flankers, Orc Scout and Tower Assassin. Despite this in general it wasn&#39;t that great. Many decks still have about 90% of their cards from the first set. <br>
<br>
There are many, many very good cards in the set. It is good to see that not all of the strong ones are rares but many of the best ones are again commons or uncommons. Some of the great cards in the set include Book of Mazarbul, Elrond, Galadriel, Long Knives of Legolas, Nenya, Voice of Nimrodel, Deep in Thought, Aragorn HttWC, Horn of Borimir, The Shards of Narsil, We Must Go Warily,  Abandoning Reason for Madness, Isengard Smith, Isengard Warrior, One Of You Must Do This, Orc Overseer, Orthanc Berserker, The Palantir of Orthanc, Saruman KoI, Saruman SotE, Orc Butcher, Orc Pillager, Orc Swordsman, Bill the Pony, Frying Pan and Gates of Argonath. <br>
<br>
I am sure that more cards will prove to be better in the long term. Cards that could end up being huge but I have rejected for now include all cards that specifically help burden, discard and pipeweed decks. At the moment they are just too weak and even though all three of these strategies have received a boost I still don&#39;t see them as being strong enough to win consistently. Once again, for all I know the world champion this year may be playing Pipeweed/discard. It just doesn&#39;t look likely to me at the moment.<br>
<br>
Before I get onto my top 10 I will go through the top cards that didn&#39;t make it into the top ten and say why. These are in spoiler order not toughness order.<br>
<br>
Elrond HtGG, yeah he is very nice giving one healing per turn but the old one is still just better so why use this one?<br>
<br>
Galadriel LotGW, very nice site control is tempting and would be good with the new Legolas but Greenleaf is still better and he doesn&#39;t care about forests. I guess as a combo her and Elrond HtGG could really let Greenleaf pump out the exertions but same as him the old version is better so she will mostly fill peoples trade folders and shop display cabinets at overinflated prices.<br>
<br>
Nenya, a really powerful ability but the two down sides are a real problem. One is spotting Galadriel, I hate cards that I potentially have to hang onto for ages. Two it happens in the regroup phase. By then it might be too late or you might have already dumped all your useless cards with Gwemegal.<br>
<br>
Voice of Nimrodel, like a Hobbit stealth for elves. Two big problems. Doesn&#39;t work at the Bridge where you most want to stealth and requires an exertion. Always better than a death though.<br>
<br>
Deep in Thought, the potential to get rid of all shadow conditions without losing yours is huge. No exertion is good. Spending the 3 in the maneuver phase is much better than in the fellowship phase. The only problem is having to spot 4 twilight to do it will make it hard to play. Some clever deck designers will use this very well but that hard to risky requirement makes Sleep C still much safer to use.<br>
<br>
We Must Go Warily, another very strong card. The problem is you have to exert a man and move twice to use it. Often that will not be possible. Aragorn could be exhausted from his archery, they might be only playing one or two huge minions and not care that much about +2 or they might have so many minions out already that you can&#39;t move. Still I think it could be very helpful in the construction of an aggressive double (triple?) move deck.<br>
<br>
One Of You Must Do This, good value inflicting probably 2-3 wounds for one exertion and a cost of 1 but it could be 1 for one and even 0 if you are really unlucky and playing against a Hobbit deck. I am also always a little scared to include too many cards that don&#39;t help you win skirmishes. Would have been better if you could do it in the Shadow Phase.<br>
<br>
Orc Overseer, a very tough minion but his very good ability will make him a big target for destruction and he has to make it to the regroup phase with 3 vitality left or he is just another big Orc.<br>
<br>
The Palantir of Orthanc, a very good ability and hard to get rid of (impossible?) as it is a support area artifact. While it is very annoying and can really slow someone cycling through their deck, trouble is by the shadow phase the Fellowship have already played their important cards. Other problem is can Uruk-Hai afford to spend 2,3,4 etc per turn to get rid of cards that their opponent will pick up again for no cost? Could wreck decks depending on events.<br>
<br>
Saruman SotE, a really annoying ability. Got a HUGE minion who would just love to play with Sam? Problems are that the rare one is much better for Uruk Hai and a cost of 4 is quite a lot to pay for something that only helps assignments not winning anything. <br>
<br>
Orc Butcher, a potential to be around STR 14 for 2 cost. How about his potential in a multiplayer game? 2 vitality makes him aimed archery fodder and if they Sleep you he is almost worthless.<br>
<br>
Orc Pillager, Aragorn with Sword, Brand, No Stranger and Bow is only STR 7 against him. Frodo with Mithril coat, Sting and the ring is STR 3! Bye bye.<br>
<br>
Orc Swordsman, give him a Vile Blade and for cost 4 you have a minion that is unlikely to lose to anything but a fully pumped dwarf. Problem is after all that he only does one wound and without a weapon is very bad value.<br>
<br>
Bill the Pony, could be useful in a denial deck that starts rare Sam or just thrown into other decks. Losing him underground is a big disadvantage and he sometimes wont help anyway as the site number is already down to 0 due to other cards in the early sites.<br>
<br>
Frying Pan, a great card. Cost 0 is nice and you can put Pippen against the Tower Assassin and watch him kick butt. Only hurts Orcs and is only STR +1. Will not replace Sting but will replace some Hobbit swords.<br>
<br>
Gates of Argonath, the anti-ARV site. Great site if you are running Dwarves or Hobbits. Downside is Thror&#39;s map will likely be running by then. Upside is Nelly can put it back in time if you are doing Nazgul. Will be popular.<br>
<br>
Those were the good and the very good. Now it is time for the great.<br>
<br>
10 Abandoning Reason for Madness, hand clog can be a real problem with Uruk-Hai and this lets you cycle your deck much faster, find that one minion you need for the upcoming battle and dump cards that are of no value in the current game. No down side to this card. I will include a couple in my deck as soon as I am allowed to.<br>
<br>
9 Orthanc Berserker, his special ability you will probably not be able to use much unless you can keep worry on the table but STR 11 and Damage +1 is just the sort of horror you love to make fierce with Savagery or Saruman.<br>
<br>
8 Aragorn HttWC, he will be a staple in denial decks. Would be rated one of the top 2-3 cards in the set except that the other two versions of Aragorn are so good.<br>
<br>
7 Isengard Warrior, makes me want to give them a try. Will there be an Isengard Orc deck that wont have 4 of there? It would be like Moria without Runners. Even has a second special ability that will occasionally cause even more havoc.<br>
<br>
6 Isengard Smith, long overdue. Now a slightly unprepared fellowship will lose their swords, bows, helms, rings, maps and even Gandalf&#39;s cart. (Insert evil laugh) Will make the Fellowship think carefully about playing a 5th companion.<br>
<br>
5 Book of Mazarbul, no more will dwarves have to go Delving. Now they can get 4 cards (not 3) every turn without an exertion. A tale that pumps Gloin. A possession. not a condition so hard to get rid of. Pity it only kicks in at site 4 but very solid.<br>
<br>
4 Horn of Borimir, like to have a STR 11 Elrond fight with you every turn? How about being able to feed an exhausted Bounder to the Cave Troll? The possibilities are endless.<br>
<br>
3 Long Knives of Legolas, so just how are we supposed to beat Legolas now? Changes him from a cowardly back row archer into a main warrior. I guess we can still use Relentless Charge and Hate.<br>
<br>
2 The Shards of Narsil, this will change the way the entire game is played. Events are back in a big way. Even lets you clear your hand if your opponent is racing to the finish. A wonderful card.<br>
<br>
1 Saruman KoI, I guess it makes sense that he is the no 1 card. He was the best evil character in the film not yet represented and this card is an excellent way of representing his power. His two abilities (all Uruk-Hai are fierce and prevent up to 3 wounds) are both huge and being site 4 is a nice bonus. He is the man. I don&#39;t suppose anyone has one that they want to trade me?<br>
<br>
Ok, if you read all of this you have done very well. I am sure that within a month other gems will be discovered and cards that seemed good now will be rotting in shoeboxes. This is just my opinion now. If you disagree please suggest sensible alternatives and don&#39;t just say &quot;The Shards of Narsil should be no 1, you are a moron, 1 star.&quot;<br>
<br>
Thanks very much for reading.<br>
